- The total number of cases is the cumulative total of all reported cases in a country;
- The number of new cases per million is the number of new cases reported per million people in the country;
- A country being "leading" in both categories means it has the highest rank (rank 1) in both the total number of cases and the number of new cases per million.

- The average vaccination coverage is calculated as the mean of the vaccination coverage percentages for each country;
- The total number of doses administered is the sum of all vaccine doses given during the vaccination campaigns;
- The total new cases per million people is the sum of new cases per million across all recorded instances;
- "Asia" refers to the continent where the country is located.

- The "best" performance is determined by a combined score of the ranks for new cases and vaccinations, where a lower score indicates better performance;
- "Managing new cases" refers to having a lower average of new cases per million people;
- "Vaccination efforts" are measured by the total number of vaccine doses administered.

- The case fatality rate (CFR) is a measure of the severity of a disease, calculated as the ratio of total deaths to total cases, typically expressed as a percentage.;
- The "most recent vaccination campaign" refers to the latest campaign in the sequence of campaigns for each country, based on the start and end dates.;
- "Weaving the strongest threads of vaccination coverage" metaphorically refers to countries with higher vaccination coverage percentages.;

- Pfizer is a pharmaceutical company that has produced one of the leading COVID-19 vaccines;
- The query focuses on campaigns with a significant number of doses administered (over 10,000) to ensure meaningful statistical analysis;
- The average cases per vaccinated individual is a measure to assess the effectiveness of the vaccination campaign in reducing the number of cases.

- The number of doses administered per million people is a common metric used to compare vaccination efforts across countries with different population sizes;
- Higher values indicate more effective or extensive vaccination campaigns;
- This metric can be influenced by factors such as government policies, public health infrastructure, and accessibility of vaccines.

- "average number of new COVID-19 cases per million" refers to the average number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 per million people in a given region or continent;
- "recovery rate" is the percentage of individuals who have recovered from COVID-19 among all confirmed cases;
- "global average" is the mean value of the average new cases per million across all continents and regions.

- 'Epicenter' refers to the country with the highest average new cases per million people;
- 'Beacon of new infections' metaphorically describes a country with a significant number of new cases;
- 'Top three countries' are determined by the highest average new cases per million people;
- 'Vaccination campaigns' refer to the efforts to vaccinate the population, measured by the percentage of the population vaccinated.

- "large population" refers to countries with a population greater than 10 million;
- "significant coverage" refers to vaccination coverage greater than 50%;
- "most successful campaigns" are ranked by the highest vaccination coverage.

- "total deaths" refers to the cumulative total of deaths due to a pandemic;
- "vaccination coverage" refers to the percentage of the population that has been vaccinated;
- "higher than average" means the total deaths are greater than the average total deaths across all countries.

- "vast population" refers to a population greater than 10 million;
- "strong shield against disease" refers to a vaccination coverage greater than 50%;
- "most protected" refers to the highest vaccination coverage.
